Grouping is primarily a social problem, and has less to do with class than is generally supposed.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree with you lots Raz, but not here. I play a mage and an enchanter. I seldom have issues getting groups with the Chanter but I do with the Mage. Is this Social? I doubt it, I turn the charm on much more with my mage to make sure I make a good impression. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I don't have to do that with the Chanter and still have no issues getting groups with my chanter.<br>
<br>
Sure if you start your groups all things are pretty equal, but if you try to get into an existing group they are not equal. Some classes are just seen as (and frankly they are) more valuable to a group, so there are more positions in groups available to them, so it is easier for them to get a group.<br>
<br>
All this to say, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> don't feel bad if you have a tough time getting a group as a mage in the low 50's, most of us were there.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Make friends cause thats the best way to get into groups as a mage. If you don't like making friends <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  make a Chanter or Cleric who are needed more often so have an inately easier time gettting into a pick up group.<br>
<br>
Nandail<br>
55th Mage on Tunare <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1052<br> <font color=#333333>(3/23/02 5:35:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Difficulty with grouping in 50+ or just cause I am a mag</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> This is just my opinion but I would not solo.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->And here I disagree.  What soloing does for me is to give me <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>control</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  Once I have mastered a particular area, I can add others to the camp, and simply increase the through put.<br>
<br>
I do the inviting, I do the pulling, and if the fish hits the fan, me and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> take care of it.<br>
<br>
Soloing a spot is just the first step to building groups there.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I seldom have issues getting groups with the Chanter but I do with the Mage. Is this Social? I doubt it<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I don't.  After all, it is a matter of convincing someone else to invite you?  What could it be other than social?  Even if you argue that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are less desired in groups, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>that</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> is largely a matter of <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>perception</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, which is again a <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>social</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> issue.<br>
<br>
I have never ever ever in 60+ levels had any problem getting a group whenever I want to.  And I attribute that to sociability.<br>
<br>
Here is one example of how to apply a little social science to the long term problem of forming groups.<br>
<br>
As I said, I master a solo spot and start inviting others.  One strategy I have done to ensure a long term supply of eager group mates is to invite substantially lower level casters to join me in my solo camp, or somewhat higher melees.  Someone around ten levels lower than me.<br>
<br>
Now I know I can solo those spawns, and as long as they don't kill themselves, I can be sure those spawns will die.  Depending on the class, they will make my job easier.  They might be a ranger and track and pull.  They might buff <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or me, or heal us between encounters.<br>
<br>
Now because I am killing things that are fairly close to my partners' levels, and fairly rapidly at that, they are getting rocking experience.  They are <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>quite</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> impressed, and remember me fondly.  They learn, with positive reinforcement, that grouping with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Cousin Raz</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> means good experience.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> MMMmmmmm....Scooby Snack!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
As for me, the experience is also good.  Being higher level, I get more than half the experience pie.  I worry less about outdamaging the pet.  The pet is stronger with buffs, and so am I, and there is less downtime and therefore more pulls.  Everybody wins.<br>
<br>
As a result, there is a long, long list of people who seek me out for experience groups, and ask me if they can please join me.<br>
<br>
And as they rise in level, they can join me more as equals.<br>
<br>
So it really IS a social problem.<br>
<br>
