<br>
Well Balanz, I partially agree with you here. Can it be wholly/primarily attributed to the social aspects of things, I have to say no. If you were to use that as a form of argument, you could literally argue everything and anything to do with others is, in its entirety a social issue. Its too one dimensional. <br>
<br>
To give an analogy...<br>
<br>
A homeless man, and a rich man both walk into a bar. The rich man has the money, which then supplies a better perception of himself through his appearance. The poor man, wearing raggy clothes, and smelling like a sewer walks in. Both order a drink, and attempt to put it on a tab. Given the circumstance of both people being unknown, if only one person is allowed to put it on their tab, in your estimation who do you think the bartender would trust to pay it back? <br>
<br>
Money is certainly very much a factor here. The homeless man, sure he could very well get it put on his tab as well. I think we could honestly agree he will have to work much much harder to do so. The reality would be the money.<br>
<br>
I've notice you posting here Balanz, you come across as very articulate and intelligent. I'm sure that helps you very much when it comes to gathering people, and creating groups. However, not everyone has these attributes..<br>
<br>
In a situation where a magician and enchanter were of equal socialability, could we honestly conclude that the magician would get the group spot? I'd conclude only in the event that the group doesn't already have an enchanter. <br>
<br>
Its a case of using your socialability to make up for the drawbacks of a class, somewhat misperceived, and somewhat lacking in the grouping skills department. People do this to get jobs etc, you got the 'hook up' so to speak. You'll do even better if you both the skills AND the social aspects down pat. One or the other can only get you so far though. <br>
<br>
As far as building your own groups, its definitely the way to go though. I have lots of success in doing that, much more so than attempting to get one. <br>
<br>
My question to you regarding this, how many times have you had to watch a magician being LFG while you selected the cleric or enchanter, or another class? Be honest <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I know there are times when I want the mage to join, many times its just so unfeasible to do so..  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/unandail.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nandail</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 356<br> <font color=#333333>(3/23/02 6:27:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Difficulty with grouping in 50+ or just cause I am a mag</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
What could it be other than social?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Inate ability of the class. That classes inate ability to fill a particular role within a group. Social seems to point to the player rather than the class. What I'm arguing is that with one class I do not have issues with another class I do. If it has to be social then I should have the same problems with my Enchanter that I have with my Mage because its me playing both, and thats simply not the case.<br>
<br>
It seems you are comparing groups you start, to being asked to join pick up groups of individuals you do not know, and those are definitely two different animals. As I said before. If you start your own groups all classes are probably equal, if you look to join pickup groups, all classes are not equal and being social affects some classes more than others in the latter situation. All this to point to the fact that mages have a tougher time getting asked to be in a random pickup group than for sure Enchanters.<br>
