<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Zebaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->: First, some strong advice.  Please take this respectfully, and as being from someone who until ten years ago had nothing but disdain for social science, and that is:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Take several social science courses.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  At least a survey of the field.  I say this, not because I think poorly of you, but because your specific example appears to show that you have not been sufficiently exposed to social science to have a good idea of what it is.  Because if you had, you would have <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>never</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> chosen that example.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> To give an analogy...A homeless man, and a rich man both walk into a bar...in your estimation who do you think the bartender would trust to pay it back?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>exactly</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> social science.  Who trusts whom, and why, there are literally <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>volumes</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> on this one subject alone.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The reality would be the money.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Well.<br>
<br>
Another important thing I learned from studying social science is about methodology.  Disregarding the fact that money is a social construct, and not objective at all, consider changing the experiments as follows.<br>
<br>
Have the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>same</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> person walk into the bar, first dressed as a homeless person, then later, dressed as a rich man.  Can you predict when they will get a tab?<br>
<br>
It doesn't matter how much money they have, what matters is how they are dressed.  For example, ever since I stopped dressing like a hippie, and wear a business suit and tie instead, I find they pay me a <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>lot</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> more money.<br>
<br>
Oh since this is social <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>science</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, you don't even need to believe me, you can test it yourself.<br>
<br>
God, I love the scientific method.  And it works on people, too!<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> In a situation where a magician and enchanter were of equal socialability<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Sigh.  So <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>many</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> unstated assumptions behind this....Better to have the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>same</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> player behind both characters.  And in that case, you would likely have an easier time getting into a pick up group.<br>
<br>
And I do understand the various <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> roles</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in a classic group, and where <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> fit, etc. etc. etc.  And still, it is a social problem.<br>
<br>
As to who I invite?  The only ones I avoid are pure melees when the group is small.  Otherwise, I care less about their class than I do them as a person.  A jerk of any class can take a hike.  A decent player of any class is welcome to join me, as long as I don't think I will have to watch them die.<br>
<br>
I love having pet centered groups, and of course seek out Magicians for those.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Inate ability of the class. That classes inate ability to fill a particular <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> role</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> within a group.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Roles</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have less objective existance than you suppose, and are primarily social contracts.  While a particular <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>style</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> of group may have certain <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>roles</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, that style of group is a social contruct, and so are the roles in it.<br>
<br>
Objectively there are only two fundamental roles in an experience group.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Damage Dealing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Damage Mitigation</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Under many circumstances, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can provide both.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If it has to be social then I should have the same problems with my Enchanter that I have with my Mage because its me playing both, and thats simply not the case.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->No, although that does eliminate innate sociability <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (the ability to get along with others)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as the deciding factor.  It does not eliminate perception or stereotypes of classes, group styles or perceived roles as issues.  All <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>social</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> issues.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You're living in a dreamworld if you think mage grouping troubles post-50 are social problems.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I am really not sure how to say this without offending people.  I will try to avoid using emotionally laden words.<br>
<br>
Much of what I am seeing here seems to stem from a lack of familiarity with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Social Science</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in general, and specific <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Social Sciences</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in particular.  Now ten years ago, I was exclusively what you would call a <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>hard</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> scientist.  My areas of interest and modest expertise included mathematics, computer science, physics, astronomy and to some extent molecular biology.  I <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>laughed</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> at the notion of <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>social</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> science.<br>
<br>
But I promise you, even a basic knowledge of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Social Psychology</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Anthropology</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would give you tremendous insight into the game, how it is played, and especially <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>why</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
<br>
Much of what you think you <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>know</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> about the game arises more from shared assumptions than any <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;objective truths&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> about the game.<br>
<br>
I am not saying that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> have no class balance issues, or that in certain group or raid situations we are less desirable than other classes.  I do claim that a major portion of that though is grounded in <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>perception</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  Nor I am saying that we cannot make useful and relatively objective statements about the game and how it is played.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> When I build groups, I frequently will start casting for what I need to fill the group...There is no reason for anyone to ever ask a mage like this.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->When I am doing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> UnHoly Trinity</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, especially <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Pet Centered Groups</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, or sometimes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> AOE groups</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, I may well seek <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Just because you have <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>selected</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> a particular group style, don't be astonished then that you seek those classes that fulfill the roles for that style.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There is no need for a mage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Unless I die and need a rez, there is no need for any class except the occasional cleric.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Grumples</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, you might think I live in a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> dream</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->world, but I respond that you have jailed yourself in a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> nightmare</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->world where your own character is unwanted.  Learn to think outside the box, examine and transcend your prejudices.<br>
<br>
If you go to the same old camps, and try to set up the same old groups, then of course you see yourself as unwanted.<br>
<br>
Go someplace new, someplace underutilized maybe, and take some <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> with you.  You won't <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>need</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> anyone else.  No clerics, no enchanters, no warriors.<br>
