: Grouping IS a social issue!</span><hr size=1> We live in the same world, but while you're quick to say that other people's <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>perception</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> is the problem, you fail to consider the other possibility.<br>
<br>
Rather than the world's perception being wrong, it might be that the world is right and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> your</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> perception is wrong.<br>
<br>
Or rather, I could agree that it is a matter of perception.  The problem is that the perception is accurate: mages bring less to a group than a large number of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> vastly more available</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> classes.<br>
<br>
Rogue and a mage LFG.  Take the rogue.<br>
Mage and a warrior LFG.  Take the warrior.<br>
Mage and a wizard LFG.  Hold out, a rogue should show up soon.<br>
<br>
This is the reality of the situation.  Rogues do a lot more damage.  People know this, and will frequently reserve a spot specifically for them, or a monk.  They may reserve a spot for and enchanter, because of clarity or crowd control.  The group usually can't even start without a healer of some sort, so they go without saying.  Mages bring very little to a group other than damage, and we don't do enough of that.<br>
<br>
No reason to hold a spot for a mage.  We're basically a hybrid class, and hybrids aren't popular.  If a paladin is LFG, I'll take him, but I'd rather have a warrior.  When I get the perfect group set up, it's usually something like me, a cleric, a warrior, a rogue, a monk and either a shaman or an enchanter.  And frankly, if anyone should get replaced in that group in the name of efficiency, it's me.  Replace me with another rogue, the group becomes more powerful.<br>
<br>
Pretty crappy, in my book.<br>
<br>
And im my experience, mages who have trouble grouping and reroll into a better class suddenly stop having trouble grouping.  The mages I know that came back as rogues or monks had a much easier time finding groups.<br>
<br>
Now a mage who can't get a group that rerolls a rogue that also can't get a group, that's a social issue.  A mage that can't get a group because his class is statistically inferior -- calling that a social issue is trying to muddy the waters.  It's a game design issue and it needs to be corrected.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ugallerus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gallerus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#333333>(3/25/02 8:01:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=163.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Grouping IS a social issue!</span><hr size=1> Make a rogue/cleric/chanter/warrior - you have NO idea how much easier it is to get a group until you do this.<br>
